{"type":"message","id":"449eabfe","parentId":"f099ed8e","timestamp":"2026-02-15T18:13:39.735Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Diagnosing the Failure**\n\nI'm currently dealing with an `AttributeError`, specifically, `client.http2` not existing. My instinct is to investigate the transport layer, perhaps `client._transport._http2`. Alternatively, I could simply rely on the `http2=True` setting. I'm leaning toward the latter for a cleaner approach. If that fails, I may move to the former, or just trust the setting and return `True`.\n\n\n**Resolving the Errors**\n\nI've made some progress on the failures. I've switched to checking `httpx.AsyncClient(http2=True)` within a try-except block to confirm h2 support. For the integration tests, I've confirmed that the test environment isn't properly configured. I'm focusing on passing `PYTHONPATH` to the subprocess to resolve this. Finally, I'll log a warning if Gitleaks is missing and address the Unicode issue by checking the presence of a cross mark in the printed report.\n\n\n**Fixing Benchmark Test**\n\nI'm now prioritizing the benchmark test. The direct check for `client.http2` won't work, so I'll wrap `httpx.AsyncClient(http2=True)` within a `try-except` block to detect h2 support. Then I'll skip the benchmark if httpx isn't installed.\n\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"edit_1771179219729_116","name":"edit","arguments":{"oldText":"async def check_http2():\n    \"\"\"Check if HTTP/2 is supported/enabled.\"\"\"\n    # This is a simplified check. In a real scenario, we'd hit an endpoint that supports H2.\n    # Here we check if the client *can* do HTTP/2.\n    async with httpx.AsyncClient(http2=True) as client:\n        return client.http2","newText":"async def check_http2():\n    \"\"\"Check if HTTP/2 is supported/enabled.\"\"\"\n    try:\n        async with httpx.AsyncClient(http2=True) as client:\n            # If we get here, h2 library is installed and http2=True is accepted\n  